Introduction

Sunspots are dark spots visible on the Suns photosphere. They are caused by strong magnetic fields which prevent heat from flowing to the Suns surface. Understanding the time series associated with the number of visible sunspots is important in tracking the Suns 11 year natural cycle. At the beginning of each 11 year cycle, the Suns magentic poles flip. As a result, solar activity increases and so does the number of sunspots. Tracking the number of sunspots through time helps scientists predict how solar activity may impact spacecraft and astronauts. This project aims to predict the overall trend of solar activity using Metas Prophet. The dataset was downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/abhinand05/daily-sun-spot-data-1818-to-2019.

filtered_SunData = SunData[SunData$Number.of.Sunspots >= 0,]

Before moving on to visualizing the data, well first group the data and calculate the average number of sunspots per year and also per month to better visualize the Suns 11 year cycle.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'

#group by year and calculate yearly average
AverageSunspotDataYearly = filtered_SunData %>% #stores our grouped data in a new data frame
    group_by(Year) %>% #this groups the data by year
    summarise(mean_Sunspots = mean(Number.of.Sunspots)) #this takes an average of the number of sunspots per year

# Group by Year and Month, then calculate the average of 'Value'
AveSunspotsMonthly = filtered_SunData %>%
    group_by(Year, Month) %>%  # Group by Year and Month
    summarise(AverageValue = mean(Number.of.Sunspots))  # Compute the average of 'Value'
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
AveSunspotsMonthly$Date = as.Date(paste(AveSunspotsMonthly$Year, AveSunspotsMonthly$Month, "01", sep = "-"))
#make the data easy to plot by converting to ts:
ts_AveSunspotsMonthly = ts(AveSunspotsMonthly$AverageValue, start = c(1818,1), frequency = 12)

Section 3: Using Prophet to Forecast the Number of Sunspots

Metas Prophet forecasting system requires the data to be in an R dataframe where the time coulmn is named ds and the data column is named y. Then after creating future dates for prophet to use in its forecast, the function predict prompts prophet to forecast the data.

3.1 Forecast using Daily Data

SunSpots.df = data.frame(ds = zoo::as.yearmon(filtered_SunData$Date.In.Fraction.Of.Year),
    y=filtered_SunData$Number.of.Sunspots)
SunSpots.df$cap = 100  # Set the cap (upper bound of sunspots)
SunSpots.df$floor = 0  # Set the floor (lower bound of sunspots)
m = prophet::prophet(SunSpots.df, changepoint.prior.scale = 0.05, growth = 'logistic')
## Disabling weekly seasonality. Run prophet with weekly.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
## Disabling daily seasonality. Run prophet with daily.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
f = prophet::make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 10, freq = 'year') #make future dates for prediction
f$cap = 200  # Cap for the future predictions needed fro logistic prediction
f$floor = 0.5   # Floor for the future predictions needed fro logistic prediction
Prediction = predict(m,f)
prophet::prophet_plot_components(m, Prediction)

plot(m,Prediction, ,type = 'line', xlab="Year", ylab='Number of Sun Spots')

This forecast provides useful information about how the number of sunspots rise and fall during each cycle, but is unable to predcit when the number of spots will rise again. This is a downfall to prophets seasonality detection.

3.2 Forecast Using Monthly Averages

Lets see if using the data that was averaged monthly yield different results.

#store our data in a data frame prophet can read
AveSunspotsMonthly.df = data.frame(ds = zoo::as.yearmon(AveSunspotsMonthly$Year),
                         y=AveSunspotsMonthly$AverageValue)
AveSunspotsMonthly.df$cap = 500  # Set the cap (upper bound of sunspots)
AveSunspotsMonthly.df$floor = 0  # Set the floor (lower bound of sunspots)
# calculate the trend
m = prophet::prophet(AveSunspotsMonthly.df, changepoint.prior.scale = 0.05, growth = 'logistic')
## Disabling weekly seasonality. Run prophet with weekly.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
## Disabling daily seasonality. Run prophet with daily.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
#calculate future dates fro prophet to use in its prediction
f = prophet::make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 20, freq = 'year') #make future dates for prediction
f$cap = 300  # Cap for the future predictions needed for logistic prediction
f$floor = 0.5   # Floor for the future predictions needed fro logistic prediction
#run a prediction of future number of sunspots
Prediction = predict(m,f)
# plot the data and prediction
plot(m,Prediction, ,type = 'line', main = 'Prophet', xlab="Year", ylab='Number of Sun Spots')

prophet::prophet_plot_components(m, Prediction)

Using the monthly averaged data yields a straight line for our trend. This is not a very useful forecast because it does not capture the rise and fall of the number of sunspots during each 11-year cycle.

3.3 Forecast Using Yearly Averages

Now we will see what the prophet forecast looks like when we average the number of sunspots each year.

#first select dates we want to use in prediction
FilteredAverageSunspotDataYearly = AverageSunspotDataYearly[AverageSunspotDataYearly$Year>=1818,]
#store our data in a data frame prophet can read
AveSunspotsYearly.df = data.frame(ds = zoo::as.yearmon(FilteredAverageSunspotDataYearly$Year),
                         y=FilteredAverageSunspotDataYearly$mean_Sunspots)
AveSunspotsYearly.df$cap = 500  # Set the cap (upper bound of sunspots)
AveSunspotsYearly.df$floor = 0  # Set the floor (lower bound of sunspots)
# calculate the trend
m = prophet::prophet(AveSunspotsYearly.df, changepoint.prior.scale = 0.05, growth = 'logistic')
## Disabling weekly seasonality. Run prophet with weekly.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
## Disabling daily seasonality. Run prophet with daily.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
#calculate future dates fro prophet to use in its prediction
f = prophet::make_future_dataframe(m, periods = 20, freq = 'year') #make future dates for prediction
f$cap = 200  # Cap for the future predictions needed fro logistic prediction
f$floor = 0.5   # Floor for the future predictions needed fro logistic prediction
#run a prediction of future number of sunspots
Prediction = predict(m,f)
# plot the data and prediction
plot(m,Prediction, ,type = 'line', main = 'Prophet', xlab="Year", ylab='Number of Sun Spots')

prophet::prophet_plot_components(m, Prediction)

Similar to what happened with the monthly averaged data, prophet forecast a flat line. Again, this is because prophet cannot recognize periodic behavior of data when the period is over a year. So instead, we are left with a line that best fits the data.

3.4 Summary

The best forecast using prophet was when the daily data was used. Prophet was able to capture how the maximums of each peak vary during each cycle. If we can combine this behavior of the peaks with the 11 year period of the sun, we can then more accurately estimate what the number of sunspots on the Sun will be in the future.

Section 4: The Suns 11 year cycle

Since Prophet cannot detect seasonality with periods longer than 1 year, I researched alternative ways to visualize and verify the 11 year cycle of the Sun.

First plot to view the data series again:

plot(AverageSunspotDataYearly[AverageSunspotDataYearly$Year>=1950,], type="line", xlab="Year", ylab="Number of Sunspots", main = "Average Number of Sunspots Measured Per Year") #visualize output
## Warning in plot.xy(xy, type, ...): plot type 'line' will be truncated to first
## character

Now we will investigate the 11 year cycle using a periodogram. A periodogram indicates strong frequencies in the data by estimating spectral density. Spectral density is a frequency domain representation of a time series, so the peaks indicate the prominent frequencies of our time series. Plotting a periodogram of our data will allow us to confirm the 11 year cycle of the Sun. First we will smooth our data using the Daniell Kernel. This is a centered moving average. For this project, we will use the parameter m = 4 which corresponds to a 9-point centered moving average. Next, we will use the command mvspec to estimate and plot the spectral density of our now smoothed time series. We see a large peak on the left of the graph which corresponds to the dominant frequency of our sunspot data. To confirm that this is the 11 year cycle, we overlay a line on the graph at the frequency 1/132 where 132 represents 12 months times 11 years. The line plotted at the frequency for 11 years matches the peak of our spectral density. This is confirmation that the Sun has an 11 year cycle. The code is as follows:

k = kernel("daniell", 4) #This is a 9-point centered moving average
astsa::mvspec(AveSunspotsMonthly$AverageValue, k, log="no")
## Bandwidth: 0.004 | Degrees of Freedom: 17.93 | split taper: 0%
abline(v=1/132, lty="dotted")
